UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: All Namibian children from ages 0â€“10 years have improved access to quality and equitable maternal, neonatal and child health, education, child protection, Early Child Development (ECD), civil registration, nutrition and Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services by 2023.

title.narrative: Capacity of services providers to provide quality and integrated health, HIV, nutrition, education, sanitation, birth registrationand child protection services improved

description.narrative: As COVID-19 overstretched systems, UNICEF prioritized continuity of essential health services and ECD access to vulnerable communities. The Community Health System was strengthened to expand essential services, capacitating 313 Community Health Workers with skills to offer additional life-saving nutrition services to 31,300 households with approximately 66,600 children across 4 regions. In Windhoek&39;s informal settlements, 5,200 children in 135 ECD centres were supported with daily meals through cash transfer, while 8000 parents and 350 Educarers were equipped with home-based learning materials for school closures. UNICEF further contributed to full COVID-19 vaccination of 14% of the population and 20% of high-risk groups.; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:05/12/2021
